<h3 id="yeast-as-an-aging-model">Yeast as an aging model</h3>
<p>Budding yeast are perhaps the simplest organism one can grow in the laboratory that ages. Thier cell division is asymmetric, with a “mother” cell producing a smaller “bud” at each cycle. Each newborn bud then lives out a lifespan of ~25 cell divisions as a mother, producing more buds. At the end of this “replicative lifespan” mother cells wrinkle up, stop reproducing, and die. Sound familiar?</p>

<p>As such, people have used it as a model to try and figure out what goes wrong in cells as they age that causes them to stop dividing and die.</p>

<p>And some people have proposed x. This violates my <a href="/the-thing">Law of Doing The Thing</a>.</p>

<h3 id="reasons-to-make-an-immortal-yeast-cell">Reasons to make an immortal yeast cell</h3>
