<h3 id="we-already-have-immortal-yeast">We already have immortal yeast</h3>
<p>One way to think about this is to consider that we already have yeast cells that don’t age. As I mentioned, <em>budding</em> yeast are used as an aging model, but another lab organism, <em>fission</em> yeast, are not. This is because they divide by symmetric <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fission_(biology)">binary fission</a>.</p>

<p>Instead of working from an aging yeast towards an immortal yeast to figure out what went wrong, lets work from the immortal cells to the aging ones.</p>

<p>How do these things live forever? A nice <a href="https://elifesciences.org/articles/20340" target="_blank">study</a> from a few years ago did a convincing job confirming what most people suspected - these cells, which divide symetrically, do not age. This is not to say that they are immortal, but that thier chances of dying do not increase with time.
One feature of aging is <a href="">Gompertzian</a> mortality. This means that the probability of death at any particular moment increases with time. An 80 year old is more likely to die on any given Tuesday than an 8 year old.</p>

<p>This increase in the <strong>hazard rate</strong> with time is not observed in several symmetrically dividing organisms.</p>

<p>They grab on to one end of the yeast cell and x:
<img src="https://static-movie-usa.glencoesoftware.com/mp4/10.7554/824/9923949731d305635f29cab1e9f7fe656247e878/elife-20340-media1.mp4" alt="fission-yeast-movie" /></p>

<p>That gives you a mortality curve that looks like this:
<img src="https://iiif.elifesciences.org/lax/20340%2Felife-20340-fig2-v3.tif/full/617,/0/default.webp" alt="fission-yeast-mortality-curve" /></p>

<p>They have a finite lifespan and die eventually, but the chances of dying do not increase with the number of cell divisions.</p>

<p>The same is true of <img src="https://advances.sciencemag.org/content/5/5/eaaw2069" alt="*E. coli*" />?</p>

